    <h1>Platform - Heroku</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <p>SLAMD is deployed to Heroku, a Platform as a Service (see also <=
a href=3D"/display/SLAMD/Conception">Conception</a> for details on the deci=
sion why we are using Heroku for the moment). It does managing of servers a=
nd containers for you and it is thus is to get started with it. Further, it=
 has a free plan where one dyno (in our case one web process) can be execut=
ed. Note, however, that Heroku might not be appropriate if at some point th=
e app must be scaled as the costs in this case increase rather quickly. Mor=
e details on the platform and on its pricings and plans can be inferred fro=
m the <a href=3D"https://devcenter.heroku.com/" class=3D"external-link" rel=
=3D"nofollow">Official Documentation</a>.</p>
<h3 id=3D"PlatformHeroku-Interacting">Interacting</h3>
<p>There a various ways of the deploying to heroku. There is a Github integ=
ration which does an automated deployment on e.g. merging into main. While =
developing we however mostly use the <a href=3D"https://devcenter.heroku.co=
m/articles/heroku-cli" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow">CLI of Hero=
ku</a>. Indeed, there is a folder called "deployment" in the root of our pr=
oject which abstracts details of the CLI commands away. It does provide scr=
ipts for deploying and creating the app, but also for management tasks such=
 as starting and stopping the app as well as checking logs. Note that these=
 tasks can also be done on the&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://dashboard.heroku.com=
/apps" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow">Dashboard</a> of a given ap=
p.</p>
